Fix __host__/__device__ math-function ambiguities in catboost CUDA kernels.

CUDA 12.x's nvcc (with newer libcudacxx) restricts which standard-math
overloads are callable from __device__ code. Bare calls like

    pow(float, float)
    ceil(float)
    log2(float)
    sqrt(float)
    abs(float)

all resolve to the host-only overload set, producing diagnostics of the form:

    error: calling a __host__ function("X(float)") from a __device__ function

CUDA's runtime math header provides explicit *f-suffixed overloads
(powf, ceilf, log2f, sqrtf, fabsf) that ARE __device__-callable. The fix
is mechanical: replace the bare call with the *f-suffixed overload when
the argument(s) are float. We leave the bare-double calls and bare-int
calls alone -- only the bare-float forms are broken.

Audited every catboost/cuda/**/*.{cu,cuh} call to bare pow/ceil/log2/
sqrt/abs and patched the ones where the argument resolves to float.

